<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41023e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41023e">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41023e"> 23(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> intervener</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In the case of a petition by a wife, no one is made a co-respondent with the husband: but a woman alleged to have committed adultery with him may usually, if she so desires, be made a party to the suit as an &ldquo;<mark>intervener</mark>&rdquo;. No claim for damages will lie against an intervener <font color="green">[unlike the case with a co-respondent or male adulterer]</font>. <small> Maud I. Crofts, <a name="MICW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MICW"><cite title="source">Women under English Law</cite></a>, 1st ed. (1925) 24</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
